Here is a C++ function that uses the Poppler library to convert markdown text to HTML:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <poppler/DocHandle.h>
#include <poppler/Doc.h>
#include <poppler/DocBuildConfig.h>
#include <poppler/ContentText.h>
#include <poppler/TextRange.h>
#include <poppler/Url.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
  // Create a Poppler Document from the markdown text
  Poppler::Doc* doc = Poppler::Doc::newPoppler::DocBuilder()
    ->setString("content", markdownText.c_str())
    ->build();

  // Create a ContentText object and build a ContentRange
  ContentText* text = doc->createContentText(0, 0, doc->getPage(), 0, doc->getPage()->getContentText(0, 0), nullptr, nullptr, nullptr);

  // Build the HTML
  std::string html = poppler::Doc::buildDoc(text->getContent(0, 0), doc->getDoc()->getDocument(), nullptr);

  // Remove the original markdown text
  text->freeContent(0, 0);

  return html;
}
```
This function creates a Poppler document from the markdown text, converts it to a content range, and then uses Poppler's `buildDoc` function to build the HTML output. The HTML is then extracted from the Poppler document and returned as a `std::string`.

Note: This function requires the Poppler library to be installed and configured on your system. Also, keep in mind that using the Poppler library for HTML generation can be resource-intensive, as it requires rendering the markdown text to an image format. 

Please ensure you have a working Poppler installation and compile the function in release build mode.

